Whether it updates automatically depends on how your site is configured.

  • GitHub Pages: If your repository is set up to have GitHub Pages build the site from the source files in the main branch, then pushing changes to index.rst and conf.py will trigger a new build automatically within a few minutes. If, instead, youre serving a prebuilt build/html directory from a separate ghpages branch, youll need to rebuild the Sphinx documentation and push the updated HTML files to that branch for the changes to appear.

  • Cloudflare: Cloudflare simply caches and serves what GitHub Pages provides. Once GitHub Pages has produced the new HTML, Cloudflare will serve it as soon as the cache expires. If you still see the old content, you can purge the cache in your Cloudflare dashboard to force the refresh.

In most cases, after pushing your changes, give it a few minutes for GitHub Pages to rebuild and Cloudflare to update. If youre using a manual build process, rebuild and deploy the HTML and then purge the Cloudflare cache to see the update immediately.
